    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_740099092" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/740099092" />
    <a title="Eilonwy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17237503-eilonwy"><img alt="Eilonwy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1506803497p2/17237503.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/740099092?book_show_action=true">Oct 12, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Eilonwy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Eilonwy" href="/user/show/17237503-eilonwy">Eilonwy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780553081312" href="/book/show/1119221.Doomsday_Book">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=just-brilliant">just-brilliant</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=character-driven">character-driven</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=diverse-characters">diverse-characters</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=beautifully-written">beautifully-written</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=tear-jerking">tear-jerking</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=deeply-thoughtful">deeply-thoughtful</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=good-mythology">good-mythology</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=heartbreaking">heartbreaking</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=heartwarming">heartwarming</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17237503-eilonwy?shelf=good-worldbuilding">good-worldbuilding</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer740099092" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14826734127167260838"><blockquote>
  <i>Kivrin Engle, a historian at Oxford University in 2054, has insisted on being allowed to time travel to medieval England, and has almost single-handedly forced it to happen despite plenty of objections from her mentor, Mr Dunworthy, who can all-too-graphically imagine every horrible thing that could possibly happen to a young woman alone in the year 1320. But the present isn’t always so safe, either. The story moves back and forth between Kivrin and Mr Dunworthy as the events in each timeline</i></blockquote></span>
  <span id="freeText14826734127167260838" style="display:none"><blockquote>
  <i>Kivrin Engle, a historian at Oxford University in 2054, has insisted on being allowed to time travel to medieval England, and has almost single-handedly forced it to happen despite plenty of objections from her mentor, Mr Dunworthy, who can all-too-graphically imagine every horrible thing that could possibly happen to a young woman alone in the year 1320. But the present isn’t always so safe, either. The story moves back and forth between Kivrin and Mr Dunworthy as the events in each timeline interleaf with each other with breathtaking, vivid intensity.</i>
</blockquote>I read this book for the first time about six years ago and barely survived it, I was so involved in everything that was happening. Connie Willis is an amazing writer, with an ability to capture both a big picture and all the little details that make me feel like I’m really there in the story. <br /><br />Those “little details” seem to be what make the difference between a Connie Willis fan and a 1-star review of her books. There are a lot of conversations where people talk over each other, around each other, and about almost anything other than what would seem to be the point of discussion, and it can be a bit frustrating and aggravating, exactly the same as it is when this happens in real life. And yet,many of the important elements of the story are revealed during these rambling conversations, subtly and sneakily. I was surprised on this reread to notice how much information I missed the first time around, and now there it was, jumping up and down and yelling, “Look at me, I’m right here!” So as a reader of Willis’s books, you’re in the exact same position as the characters, trying to figure out what’s important and what’s just distraction. <br /><br />In this story, neither the past nor the future is what you might expect. No matter how well we study the past and think we know what it sounded like, or smelled like, or what the rules of social deportment were, we weren’t really there and we can’t really know -- we just guess. It’s impossible to be truly prepared for such experiences. And the future in this book, which was published in 1992, has time travel and video phones, but no mobile phones. The first time I read this (in 2012), that drove me nuts. This time I was prepared, and I was able to read it as an alternate universe. <br /><br />The important thing with this book is: All that calm analysis that I just wrote above does not in any way convey how intense, philosophical, thought-provoking, deeply moving, and heartbreaking this book is. The problem is, there is no way to show any of that in a review. But those are the elements that make this a science fiction classic, and which make it worth reading, and reading more than once. There’s just enough sense of the absurd (“The Mass in the Time of Pestilence,” for instance) to balance the heartbreak. But if you read this, I recommend finishing it someplace where you can have at least a few minutes to yourself. <br /><br />Also, this book will make you extremely sensitive to anyone coughing, sniffling, and scratching in your vicinity. <br /><br />I’m not sure this is any kind of helpful review whatsoever. But 5 stars for this book the first time I read it, and another 5 stars now. <br /><br />Also, thanks to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/900716391?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1" rel="nofollow noopener">Sarah</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2109898544?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1" rel="nofollow noopener">Elena</a> for BR’ing it with me this time. Being able to discuss it was great. &lt;3</span>
  <a data-text-id="14826734127167260838" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


